can be a necessity for self-care, but Hagood argues our efforts to shield ourselves can also decrease our tolerance for sonic and social difference. Challenging our self-defeating attempts to be free of one another, he rethinks media theory, sound studies, and the very definition of media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aCommunication and culturezUnited States. 0aHeadphonesxHealth aspects. 0aInformation technologyxHealth aspects. 0aMass mediaxInfluence. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspects. 0aNoise (Philosophy) 0aNoise (Philosophy). 0aNoise controlxEquipment and supplies. 0aNoisexPhysiological effect. 0aPopular culturexEffect of technological innovations on. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478004479zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478004479423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478004479.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles